title: Consider adding `isNullish` as an alias for `isNil`

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
With the addition of features such as the "[Nullish coalescing operator](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Nullish_coalescing)" and the "[Nullish coalescing assignment](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Nullish_coalescing_assignment)", I believe the more idiomatic name for this function should be `isNullish`. Of course, for backwards compatibility, it makes sense to add this as an alias —or perhaps make `isNil` the alias? (no strong opinion there).

I understand that [lodash has been striving to reduce (or eliminate) aliases for quite some time](https://github.com/lodash/lodash/issues/4057#issuecomment-437979593). In this case, however, I believe it is worthwhile to give it some thought.

Is this something worth considering?

title: Set permissions to test.yml

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
Hi, I'm from Google and I'm working with the OpenSSF to improve supply chain security in many open source projects.

Github workflows are granted write-all permission by default, which allow an attacker to exploit these permissions in case of a compromised workflow. Thus, it is both a recommendation from the [OpenSSF Scorecard](https://github.com/ossf/scorecard/blob/main/docs/checks.md#token-permissions) and the [Github](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/security-guides/security-hardening-for-github-actions) itself to always use credentials that are minimally scoped.

This means setting the [top level](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#permissions) permission as contents: read (usually enough to most actions) or even read-all, and grant any write permission at the [job level](https://docs.github.com/en/actions/using-workflows/workflow-syntax-for-github-actions#jobsjob_idpermissions)

Let me know if that's ok for you and I will open a PR setting permissions on tests.yml.

title: flow & compose TypeScript types permit invalid compositions

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
(Apologies if TypeScript issues should be opened somewhere else, like at DefinitelyTyped.  Happy to open one there if that's the right thing.)

The TS types for `flow` and `compose` from `@types/lodash` permit invalid compositions.   Here's a minimal example with `flow`:

```ts
import flow from 'lodash/fp/flow'
​
declare const f1: (n: number) => string
declare const f2: (n: string) => boolean
​
// Ok, good
const g1 = flow(f1, f2)
​
// This should be a type error! f1 is not composable with f1
const g2 = flow(f1, f1)
```

[TypeScript Playground link to the above example](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#code/JYWwDg9gTgLgBAcgDYQCYEMDOALBcD0+cAcgKamoVwwRwBm0AxqXACoDKcYS6AngOZQIAVwB2qarWCjMMdEiRwUGHADo22FqNIAPeEmkt5EbXGCZRCeJmF06wRsFKiYAKFCRY9FAHd6QkERlLGx8OjAw3wRXV0pGHigWRhNZegBGAC44AApRLNFhEAAjUigASjgAXgA+OFkoaX5Y0nj0RLhkmXg6ACYs3Kz6xoqauCKICCRSdFEYwjgAeQBrABo4fgnUV07U-jSq7wgfbLo0td6yuaJWbHM67BEkCRK4dGpeMBZSoSgAQnSzJg4KIIPBkuAIJh0EUpnAfMAYNh0tsUvB+D0DnRfCczulLkA)

### Expected behavior

`flow(f1, f1)` should be a type error, since `(number) => string` isn't composable with `(number) => string`.  `compose(f1, f1)` similarly isn't a type error.  This allows invalid compositions that will likely fail at runtime.

### Actual behavior

`flow(f1, f1)` is not a type error.

---

It looks like the the current types don't error because of the [catchall overload](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/blob/master/types/lodash/fp.d.ts#L1327).  When none of the strongly typed overloads match, TS uses the catchall, which accepts any argument list of functions.

My colleagues and I started using lodash/fp on a new TypeScript project where function composition is an important part of our toolbox.  This issue is a blocker for our using lodash.

While I'm hoping for a solution, I also understand it may not be possible.  In that case I'm just hoping to learn about why the current types are what they are.  I figure there might be some history and backward compatibility concerns that drove the current types.

Thanks!

---

Update: added TS Playground link

title: [Question] : Multiple predicates for _.filter
body:
Hello, I am trying to use lodash and I was wondering when we run multiple `_.filter()` against a data set, can we have a array of predicates as a parameter. 

For example (Current usage) : 
```
const cars = [
  { 'company': 'Honda', 'year': '2019', 'name': 'civic' },
  { 'company': 'Honda', 'year': '2020', 'name': 'civic' },
  { 'company': 'Hyundai', 'year': '2019', 'name': 'elantra' }
];
const civicFilterResult = _.filter(cars, { 'name': 'civic' }); <----- results for civic
const elantraFilterResult = _.filter(cars, { 'name': 'elantra' }); <---- results for elantra
```

Refactored usage : 

```
const cars = [
  { 'company': 'Honda', 'year': '2019', 'name': 'civic' },
  { 'company': 'Honda', 'year': '2020', 'name': 'civic' },
  { 'company': 'Hyundai', 'year': '2019', 'name': 'elantra' }
];
const filteredResults = _.filter(cars, [{ 'name': 'civic' }, { 'name': 'elantra' }]); <---- results for civic and elantra
```
**Note**: Keep in mind I don't mean I want `if(name === 'civic' && name === 'elantra')`, I want both of them in separate result sets. 

**Questions**

- Can the above be achieved in any different way ?
- If we do it the current way is there a performance hit with large data sets like 200 complex collections ? 


Let me know if something is not clear, I'm relatively new to lodash usage and was wondering if this is something possible. Thanks !

title: isMatch does not work correctly with sparse arrays

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
### One might expect that:
```
isMatch(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['a', , 'c']) === true
```

### Current behaviour is:
```
isMatch(['a', 'b', 'c'], ['a', , 'c']) === false
isMatch(['a', undefined, 'c'], ['a', , 'c']) === true
```

### Workaround:
```
isMatch(['a', 'b', 'c'], {...['a', , 'c']}) === true
isMatch(['a', undefined, 'c'], {...['a', , 'c']}) === true
```

### Motivation:
Considering arrays' underlying objects:
<dl>
<dt>1º [ 'a', 'b', 'c' ]</dt>
<dd>{ 0: 'a', 1: 'b', 2: 'c' }</dd>
<dt>2º [ 'a', , 'c' ]</dt>
<dd>{ 0: 'a', 2: 'c' }</dd>
<dt>3º [ 'a', undefined, 'c' ]</dt>
<dd>{ 0: 'a', 1: undefined, 2: 'c' }</dd>
</dl>

`isMatch` on array and on object gives conflicting results:

| test | array | object |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `isMatch(1º, 2º)` |  false | true |
| `isMatch(2º, 3º)` |  true | false |


### Summary:
`['a', , 'c']` is not equal to `['a', undefined, 'c']` and shouldn't be treated so.

title: Use negation instead direct null or undefined check

labels.name: issue bankruptcy
labels.description: Closing the issue/PR to start fresh

body:
Instead of checking if a value is null or undefined using a negation, makes it is much cleaner with exactly the same behavior.
For example, instead of this
https://github.com/lodash/lodash/blob/2da024c3b4f9947a48517639de7560457cd4ec6c/cond.js#L31
It looks much more readable and non-hacky
```js
 const length = !pairs ? pairs.length : 0 
```
In JS `==` is used if the left-hand side value and the right-hand side value are null or undefined, however, `===` fixes it where `null` is no longer equal to `undefined`. It isn't a must "needed" refactor, however, it improves readability and those old-style equality checks.
